column169: XPO Logistics terminal UDV experienced a UN2734 Tri-Act 1825 release from a 330-gallon metal tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5-gallons of product released to a 2’ x 1’ area of the wood trailer floor and tote body due to the cap coming off in transit. The cap was re-secured to the tote. The impacted tote and trailer floor were cleaned with pads and simple green. The impacted rags and PPE were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column169: On June 4, 2024, two (2) 50-pound bags of lithium hydroxide were torn in transit and released approximately less than one (<1) pound of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental Services (GES) to remediate the impacted site. GES personnel utilized absorbents and hand tools to remediate the lithium hydroxide-impacted trailer. All waste was collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and one (1) 5-gallon bucket for disposal.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal LBY experienced a UN1789 Blue Whale Muriatic Acid pH Reducer release from multiple boxes each containing (2) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of product released to 1’ x 1’ area of the trailer floor and a 3’ x 3’ area of the concrete dock due to the jugs being crushed in transit. Sodium bicarbonate was deployed to clean and neutralize the impacted areas. A total of (20) 1-gallon jugs, impacted cardboard, and impacted absorbents were collected and containerized into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: DURING NORMAL HANDLING PROCESS AT THE UPS HONG KONG INTERNATIONAL CHEK LAP KOK FACILITY ONE AIR PACKAGE FROM HONG KONG DESTINED TO THE USA WAS OBSERVED SMOKING ON THE BELT. THE PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN AWAY FROM THE BELT AND PLACED IN A SEGREGATED AREA. THE SMOLDERING INCREASED AND SUBSEQUENTLY THE PACKAGE BEGAN BURNING. UPS STAFF USED A FIRE EXTINGUISHER TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. THE EVENT WAS DISCOVERED PRIOR TO THE PACKAGE BEING LOADED INTO AN AIR CONTAINER. THE PACKAGE HAD PASSED A DANGEROUS GOODS ACCEPTANCE AUDIT PRIOR TO THE LITHIUM BATTERY INCIDENT. THE PACKAGE WAS FULLY DECLARED WITH AN APPROPRIATE IATA SHIPPERS DECLARATION AS UN3480 LITHIUM ION BATTERIES, SECTION IA OF PACKING INSTRUCTION 965. AFTER THE EVENT WAS EXTINGUISHED, THE OPERATIONS NOTED THE INNER THREE BATTERIES WERE NOT PROPERLY SEPARATED OR PROTECTED. ADDITIONALLY, NO WATT HOUR MARKINGS WERE FOUND ON THE BATTERIES.  PER 49CFR 171.15, THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS CONTACTED BY TELEPHONE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THE OFFICER WAS UNABLE TO ACCEPT THE TELEPHONE REPORT DUE TO THE EVENT NOT OCCURRING IN THE USA.
